  { q: 'Is Horseshoe Bay a good real estate investment?', a: 'Lakefront and golf-course-adjacent properties have appreciated steadily for two decades and tend to hold value because supply is structurally limited - Lake LBJ has finite frontage, and city limits cap new development. Short-term rental potential is strong; many owners offset carrying costs through resort-area vacation rental income.' },
  { q: 'What schools serve Horseshoe Bay?', a: 'Horseshoe Bay is split between Marble Falls ISD (south side) and Llano ISD (north side). Most full-time families live on the Marble Falls ISD side, which has higher enrollment and more program depth. Both districts are well-rated for the rural Hill Country region.' },
  { q: 'Do Horseshoe Bay homes come with a country club membership?', a: 'Many - but not all - homes convey with Horseshoe Bay Resort & Country Club membership, which gives access to the three golf courses, Yacht Club, marinas, dining, and amenities. Always confirm membership status and any transfer fees during the offer process; this can swing total cost meaningfully.' },
  { q: 'What is the property tax rate in Horseshoe Bay?', a: 'Property tax rates in Horseshoe Bay are notably lower than in Austin proper - typically 1.6 to 1.9 percent vs. Austin\'s 2.0 to 2.4 percent - because there is no MUD or PID overlay in most areas, and Texas has no state income tax. For high-value homes, this is a meaningful long-term savings vs. an equivalent Austin property.' }
